Some Observations:¶

  • Green Bay throughout the years is techically a small area/population, but has a surprisingly high percentage of wins over the course of time.
  • My personal opinion is that a lot of cities are 'sport towns', whether they are large in population or not...but we will let the data speak for itself.
  • I also believe that some years there are a lot of good teams, and when everyone plays against each other, many win percentages arent high because all the teams caused occassional losses with other teams. In other words, not every year do you have a distribution of teams that range uniformly from great to good to ok to bad to terrible, sometimes you actually have years where in one division or season there are MANY good teams, and thus your win percentage will be lower just based on the data. This may skew our results slightly, its just something to keep in mind.
  • Sometimes teams are carried by star players (anomalies), who can swing the win percentage in major ways...
  • What we do see in some of the data is that the top three largest metropolitan areas sometimes have teams that have suprisingly low winning percentages !



Approach:¶

  • We have four main source of data:

    • nba.csv: NBA Basketball related information
    • mlb.csv: MLB Baseball related information
    • nhl.csv: NHL Hockey related information
    • wikipedia_data.html: Master reference mapping sports teams to specific Metropolitan markets, Population, etc.
  • Create our core dataframe cities which will contain information such as all Metro areas, Populations, and sport team data
  • Create individual dataframes for each sport, which encompass specifically the team name and its calculated winning percentage
    • These dataframes will have a form that includes the sport name, i.e. nfl (football related), nba (basketball related), mlb (baseball related), nhl(hockey related)
  • Clean data extremely thoroughly, removing elements/strings not needed
  • Combine dataframes
  • Create a set of 'mapping' dictionaries (mapping the team name to its Metropolitan area and Population)
  • Correlation analysis between overall Metropolitan population and team winning percentages

Description¶

In this assignment you must read in a file of metropolitan regions and associated sports teams from assets/wikipedia_data.html and answer some questions about each metropolitan region. Each of these regions may have one or more teams from the "Big 4": NFL (football, in assets/nfl.csv), MLB (baseball, in assets/mlb.csv), NBA (basketball, in assets/nba.csv or NHL (hockey, in assets/nhl.csv). Please keep in mind that all questions are from the perspective of the metropolitan region, and that this file is the "source of authority" for the location of a given sports team. Thus teams which are commonly known by a different area (e.g. "Oakland Raiders") need to be mapped into the metropolitan region given (e.g. San Francisco Bay Area). This will require some human data understanding outside of the data you've been given (e.g. you will have to hand-code some names, and might need to google to find out where teams are)!

For each sport I would like you to answer the question: what is the win/loss ratio's correlation with the population of the city it is in? Remember that to calculate the correlation with pearsonr, so you are going to send in two ordered lists of values, the populations from the wikipedia_data.html file and the win/loss ratio for a given sport in the same order. Average the win/loss ratios for those cities which have multiple teams of a single sport. Each sport is worth an equal amount in this assignment (20%*4=80%) of the grade for this assignment.

In addition, I would like you to explore the hypothesis that given that an area has two sports teams in different sports, those teams will perform the same within their respective sports. How I would like to see this explored is with a series of paired t-tests (so use ttest_rel) between all pairs of sports. Are there any sports where we can reject the null hypothesis? Again, average values where a sport has multiple teams in one region. Remember, you will only be including, for each sport, cities which have teams engaged in that sport, drop others as appropriate. This question is worth 20% of the grade for this assignment.

#---     CREATING FOUR DFS, MAPPING A TEAM WITH A METRO AREA  ---

t1 = cities[['NFL','METRO']].copy()
t1 = t1[t1.NFL != ''].reset_index(drop=True)#  Removing rows with missing strings

#  Note:  I have to break out metro areas that have multiple teams of the same sport ! 
t1 = t1.append({'NFL' : 'Giants' , 'METRO' : 'New York City'} , ignore_index=True)
t1 = t1.append({'NFL' : 'Jets' , 'METRO' : 'New York City'} , ignore_index=True)
t1 = t1.append({'NFL' : 'Rams' , 'METRO' : 'Los Angeles'} , ignore_index=True)
t1 = t1.append({'NFL' : 'Chargers' , 'METRO' : 'Los Angeles'} , ignore_index=True)
t1 = t1.append({'NFL' : '49ers' , 'METRO' : 'San Francisco Bay Area'} , ignore_index=True)
t1 = t1.append({'NFL' : 'Raiders' , 'METRO' : 'San Francisco Bay Area'} , ignore_index=True)
t1.METRO = t1.METRO.str.strip()#  clean whitespaces to be safe 


t1 = t1[3:].reset_index(drop=True)  # THIS IS NOW A TRUE MAPPER FOR NFL TEAMS TO METRO AREAS

In [205]:
#  Some visual references (below) to understand the correlation values:

Translation:

  • 0 indicates no linear relationship

  • +1 indicates a perfect positive linear relationship: as one variable increases in its values, the other variable also increases in its values via an exact linear rule.

  • -1 indicates a perfect negative linear relationship: as one variable increases in its values, the other variable decreases in its values via an exact linear rule.

  • Values between 0 and 0.3 (0 and -0.3) indicate a weak positive (negative) linear relationship via a shaky linear rule.

  • Values between 0.3 and 0.7 (-0.3 and -0.7) indicate a moderate positive (negative) linear relationship via a fuzzy-firm linear rule.

  • Values between 0.7 and 1.0 (-0.7 and -1.0) indicate a strong positive (negative) linear relationship via a firm linear rule.

def nhl_correlation(): 
    population_by_region = nhl2.Population 
    win_loss_by_region = nhl2.WIN_PCT      
    return stats.pearsonr(population_by_region, win_loss_by_region)

#---  CREATING SPORT DATAFRAMES FROM RAW DATA  ---
pd.set_option('mode.chained_assignment', None)
mlb_df=pd.read_csv("assets/mlb.csv")
nhl_df=pd.read_csv("assets/nhl.csv")
nba_df=pd.read_csv("assets/nba.csv")
nfl_df=pd.read_csv("assets/nfl.csv")


pd.options.display.float_format = '{:,.4f}'.format



#-----------------------------[NFL]-------------------------------------

#---  MATCH BASED ON TEAMNAME NOT CONTAINING AFC OR NFC  ---
cl_nfl_df = nfl_df[~nfl_df['team'].str.contains('AFC|NFC')].copy()

#---  REMOVE THE CHARACTER * AND + FROM THE RIGHT HAND SIDE OF CERTAIN CELLS  ---
cl_nfl_df.team = cl_nfl_df['team'].map(lambda x: x.rstrip('+|*'))
#clean_nfl_df['team'] = clean_nfl_df['team'].map(lambda x: str(x)[:-1])

#---  FINAL CLEAN AND CHECK  ---
cl_nfl_df.team = cl_nfl_df['team'].str.strip()  # just to make sure


f_nfl_df = cl_nfl_df#   new copy so i can reuse if i need to  
#  ---  WINS AND LOSES ARE NEVER FRACTIONS !  ---
f_nfl_df.W = f_nfl_df.W.astype('int64')#   convert column W to type integer
f_nfl_df.L = f_nfl_df.L.astype('int64')#   convert column L to type integer 

f_nfl_df['WIN_PCT'] = f_nfl_df['W'] / (f_nfl_df['L'] + f_nfl_df['W'])#   create NEW column:  WIN_PCT

f_nfl = f_nfl_df[ ['team','WIN_PCT', 'year'] ] #         return only specific cols

print("\nNFL dataframe created...\n")


#-----------------------------[NBA]-------------------------------------

cl_nba_df = nba_df[~nba_df['team'].str.contains('Division')].copy()

cl_nba_df['team'] = cl_nba_df['team'].str.extract(r'([A-Z].*[a-z])', expand=False)
cl_nba_df.team = cl_nba_df['team'].str.strip()  # just to make sure

f_nba_df = cl_nba_df 
f_nba_df.W = f_nba_df.W.astype('int64')
f_nba_df.L = f_nba_df.L.astype('int64') 
f_nba_df['WIN_PCT'] = f_nba_df['W'] / (f_nba_df['L'] + f_nba_df['W'])
f_nba = f_nba_df[ ['team','WIN_PCT', 'year']]
f_nba.reset_index(inplace = True, drop=True) 

print("\nNBA dataframe created...")


#-----------------------------[MLB]-------------------------------------

#---  MATCH BASED ON YEAR 2016  ---
cl_mlb_df = mlb_df.copy()
cl_mlb_df.team = cl_mlb_df['team'].str.strip()  


f_mlb_df = cl_mlb_df 
f_mlb_df.W = f_mlb_df.W.astype('int64')
f_mlb_df.L = f_mlb_df.L.astype('int64') 

f_mlb_df['WIN_PCT'] = f_mlb_df['W'] / (f_mlb_df['L'] + f_mlb_df['W'])

f_mlb = f_mlb_df[ ['team','WIN_PCT', 'year']]
f_mlb.reset_index(inplace = True, drop=True) 

print("\nMLB dataframe created...")


#-----------------------------[NHL]-------------------------------------


cl_nhl_df = nhl_df.copy()
cl_nba_df = nba_df[~nba_df['team'].str.contains('Division')].copy()
cl_nhl_df =  cl_nhl_df[~cl_nhl_df.team.str.contains("Division")]
cl_nhl_df.team = cl_nhl_df['team'].map(lambda x: x.rstrip('*'))
cl_nhl_df.team = cl_nhl_df['team'].str.strip()

def sports_team_performance(): 
    
    # Note: p_values is a full dataframe, so df.loc["NFL","NBA"] should be the same as df.loc["NBA","NFL"]
    # and df.loc["NFL","NFL"] should return np.nan
    
    
    sports = ["MLB","NBA","NFL","NHL"]

    p_values=pd.DataFrame({k:np.nan for (k) in ["NFL","NBA","NHL","MLB"]},index=sports)
    return p_values
